d in migrations 0009/0010 for compactions/runs/run_events (Drizzle can't emit it) — matches the documented pattern from migration 0004.\n- `RunAbortRegistry.abort()` has no ownership check itself, but is only ever invoked after `RunsRepository.requestCancel` (userId-scoped) succeeds — no path to abort another tenant's run.\n- TRUST_PROXY defaults to unset (fail-closed: doesn't trust X-Forwarded-For unless explicitly configured) — correct.\n- Throttling: ThrottlerGuard registered before SessionAuthGuard in APP_GUARD order (rejects floods before paying session lookup cost); stricter per-route @Throttle on register/login.\n- CI workflow: zizmor scan returned zero findings; all actions pinned to commit SHA with version comments, `persist-credentials: false`, no `pull_request_target`, no untrusted input interpolated into `run:` steps.\n- No secrets in `.env.example` diff; no API-key/token values found in any `logger.*`/`console.log` call in the touched model/run files.\n\nOne thing I did NOT get to verify empirically (time-boxed): whether `chats-rls.integration.spec.ts` actually asserts cross-tenant denial for `runs`/`run_events`/`compactions` specifically (vs. just chats/messages as in the original suite). Recommend a quick grep of that spec before merge to confirm coverage matches the new tables.\n</teammate-message>\n\n<teammate-message teammate_id=\"security-review\" color=\"yellow\">\n{\"type\":\"idle_notification\",\"from\":\"security-review\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-02T09:20:11.806Z\",\"idleReason\":\"available\"}\n</teammate-message>\n\n<teammate-message teammate_id=\"security-review\" color=\"yellow\" summary=\"Re-sending completed security review report\">\nReview is complete — already sent in full (msg_id 3ea6a42c) but re-stating in case it was missed:\n\nNO HIGH-SEVERITY FINDINGS on experiment/overnight-loop vs master.\n\nScope covered (read in full, not just diffs): apps/api/src/auth/* (session-auth.guard.ts, sessions.repository.ts, auth.service.ts, auth.controller.ts, session-cleanup.service.ts, app.setup.ts/app.module.ts guard wiring), apps/api/src/chats/{runs.controller.ts, run-stream-bridge.ts, chats.controller.ts, runs-worker.service.ts, chat-loop.service.ts, run-execution.service.ts, runs-repository.ts, run-abort-registry.ts, dto/runs.dto.ts}, apps/api/src/db/{tenant-db.service.ts, schema/chats.ts}, migrations 0009-0015, apps/api/src/queue/*, .github/workflows/ci.yml (+ zizmor scan, clean).\n\n4 low/informational findings, ranked:\n\n1. [LOW] runs-repository.ts:236 `RunEventsRepository.append` — insert relies on the `run_events_owner` RLS policy's single `USING` clause also acting as `WITH CHECK` (correct Postgres semantics, confirmed via migration 0010 SQL). Not a bug, but unverified whether `chats-rls.integration.spec.ts` has a test asserting a forged cross-tenant `run_id` INSERT into `run_events` is rejected — recommend confirming before merge. No exploit scenario found; this is a coverage gap, not a vulnerability.\n\n2. [INFO] sessions.repository.ts:173 `deleteExpired` is intentionally cross-user (sessions table has no RLS, documented as pre-auth necessity) but only reachable via the internal pg-boss cron consumer in session-cleanup.service.ts — no client-reachable path. No finding.\n\n3. [INFO] Queue payloads (`RunJob`/`RunTimeoutJob` in runs-worker.service.ts) carry `userId`, but `QUEUE.enqueue()` is only ever called server-side post-auth (chat-loop.service.ts, session-cleanup.service.ts) — confirmed no controller writes to the queue directly, so \"forged queue payload crosses tenants\" is not a reachable attack surface.\n\n4. [INFO] run-execution.service.ts:173,180 persists raw `error.message` into `run_events.payload`/`runs.error`, re-served to the run's owner via SSE/`/runs/:id`. Only the owner can read it (RLS + `findOwnedRun` verified), so not cross-tenant leakage — flagging only because a BYOK provider could theoretically embed sensitive detail in an error string.\n\nEverything else checked out clean: fail-closed global `SessionAuthGuard` (APP_GUARD) with minimal correctly-scoped `@Public()` usage, atomic `findActiveAndTouch` (no TOCTOU), all run/chat endpoints derive identity solely from `@CurrentUser()` with 404/204 on cross-tenant ids (no existence leak), FORCE RLS confirmed on all new tables (compactions/runs/run_events), `RunAbortRegistry.abort()` only invoked after ownership-verified `requestCancel`, TRUST_PROXY fail-closed default, throttler ordered before session guard, CI actions pinned to SHA with `persist-credentials: false` and no untrusted input in run steps, no secrets in `.env.example` diff or in any logging call touched by this branch.\n</teammate-message>\n\n<teammate-message teammate_id=\"security-review\" color=\"yellow\">\n{\"type\":\"idle_notification\",\"from\":\"security-review\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-02T09:20:33.941Z\",\"idleReason\":\"available\"}\n</teammate-message>\n\n<teammate-message teammate_id=\"security-review\" color=\"yellow\" summary=\"Final report — no high-severity findings (already sent twice)\">\nConfirming final: review is complete and was already delivered in full twice (msg_id 3ea6a42c and 461a83e8). Summary for close-out:\n\nNO HIGH-SEVERITY FINDINGS on experiment/overnight-loop vs master.\n\n4 low/informational findings:\n1. [LOW] runs-repository.ts:236 — RunEventsRepository.append's write-side safety depends on RLS USING-doubles-as-WITH-CHECK (correct, verified in migration 0010 SQL). Recommend confirming chats-rls.integration.spec.ts actually tests a forged cross-tenant run_id insert into run_events before merge — this is a possible test-coverage gap, not a confirmed vulnerability.\n2. [INFO] sessions.repository.ts:173 deleteExpired is intentionally cross-user, only reachable via internal cron consumer — no finding.\n3. [INFO] Queue payloads carry userId but QUEUE.enqueue() is never client-reachable — confirmed no exploitable path.\n4. [INFO] run-execution.service.ts:173,180 persists raw error.message into run_events/runs.error, served back only to the owning user — not cross-tenant, minor mention only.\n\nEverything else (fail-closed global auth guard, atomic session validation, FORCE RLS on all new tables, ownership checks before every mutation, TRUST_PROXY/throttle ordering, clean CI/zizmor, no secrets in diff) checked out clean. OK to close.\n</teammate-message>\n\n<teammate-message teammate_id=\"security-review\" color=\"yellow\">\n{\"type\":\"idle_notification\",\"from\":\"security-review\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-02T09:25:27.732Z\",\"idleReason\":\"available\"}\n</teammate-message>\n\n<teammate-message teammate_id=\"concurrency-review\" color=\"purple\" summary=\"Correctness/concurrency review findings for run pipeline\">\nAdversarial correctness/concurrency review of experiment/overnight-loop vs master, durable-run pipeline. 5 findings, all HIGH except the last (MEDIUM). No security/style findings included per scope.\n\n---\n\n**1. [HIGH] At-least-once queue delivery causes concurrent duplicate execution of the same run — no fencing anywhere in the pickup path.**\n\n- `apps/api/src/queue/pgboss-queue.service.ts:19-24` (`DEFAULT_QUEUE_OPTIONS`) and `:46-67` (`ensureQueue`) never set `expireInSeconds`, so pg-boss's own default applies: verified in `node_modules/.pnpm/pg-boss@12.24.1/.../dist/plans.js:28` → `QUEUE_DEFAULTS.expire_seconds = FIFTEEN_MINUTES` (900s), with `retryLimit: 3` set locally.\n- `apps/api/src/chats/runs-worker.service.ts:90-94` calls `boss.work()` with no per-job `expireInSeconds` override either.\n- Interleaving: a run whose model call runs ≥15 min (long completion, slow/hung provider) is marked expired by pg-boss while the original `executeJob` handler promise is still executing (Node doesn't preempt in-flight async work). With `retryLimit: 3`, pg-boss redelivers the same job. The redelivered `executeJob` (`runs-worker.service.ts:154-181`) reads the run: status is `running_model` (non-terminal) and `cancelRequestedAt` is null → skip-gate passes → it calls `runExecution.executeRun(...)` again.\n- `run-execution.service.ts:109-117` calls `RunsRepository.markStarted(...)` and **never checks the returned value**. `markStarted`'s WHERE guard (`runs-repository.ts:94-122`) only excludes *terminal* statuses — it has no \"must currently be `queued`\" check — so the second call succeeds, resets `startedAt`/`heartbeatAt`, and a **second concurrent model call** is issued for the same run.\n- Consequence: both instances append `model.delta` events under the same `runId`. `run_events.sequence` is a table-global identity (`schema/chats.ts:257-259`), and readers filter by `run_id` + `ORDER BY sequence` (`runs-repository.ts:253-272`, `run-stream-bridge.ts:140-146`) — so a client replaying the event log sees **interleaved deltas from two independent generations** as one scrambled text stream. Both `onFinish` handlers race on `persistAssistantMessage` (`run-execution.service.ts:302-344`): whichever's `findTurnState` read happens last wins via `updateAssistantReply`, silently discarding the other generation's answer. Plus doubled LLM cost.\n- No existing test simulates redelivery/expiry — `worker-mode.e2e-spec.ts` only exercises single-delivery paths (grepped for redeliver/concurrent/race/idempot — 0 hits).\n\n---\n\n**2. [HIGH] Cancellation is silently dropped if it lands during the worker's pickup window (TOCTOU between skip-gate read and abort registration).**\n\n- `runs-worker.service.ts:154-181` (skip-gate) reads run state once, then at `:185` does `await this.models.resolveModelCredential(job.userId)` (network/DB round trip), and only at `:191` calls `this.aborts.register(job.runId)`.\n- If `PATCH /api/v1/runs/:id` (`runs.controller.ts:90-104`) arrives in that window: `requestCancel` (`runs-repository.ts:166-186`) succeeds (WHERE only excludes terminal + already-requested), stamping `cancel_requested_at`. But `this.aborts.abort(id)` (`run-abort-registry.ts:28-35`) is a no-op — nothing is registered yet for that runId.\n- Execution proceeds to `runs-worker.service.ts:191` and registers a **fresh, non-aborted** `AbortController`. `RunExecutionService.executeRun`'s `markStarted` call (`run-execution.service.ts:110`, `runs-repository.ts:94-122`) **never checks `cancelRequestedAt`** — its WHERE guard only excludes terminal statuses. The model call proceeds to completion; the run finishes normally as `completed`. `cancel_requested_at` is left stamped on a completed run and nothing ever re-consults it afterward.\n- User-visible effect: clicking \"stop\" during this narrow window (one credential-resolution round trip) is silently ignored — the full answer streams anyway. This is distinct from the already-documented \"mid-flight cross-process cancellation\" gap (`run-abort-registry.ts:9-11` acknowledges that as deferred to LISTEN/NOTIFY) — this race exists **within the current single co-located process**, same-process, today.\n- Not covered by `worker-mode.e2e-spec.ts:270` (\"PATCH cancelled stops an executing run mid-flight\") — that test almost certainly cancels well after registration, not during startup.\n\n---\n\n**3. [HIGH] `executeRun` proceeds with a full (paid) model call even when `markStarted`'s guard rejects the transition — and appends events to already-terminal runs.**\n\n- `run-execution.service.ts:109-117`: `markStarted` is called and its return value discarded. If the run is already terminal at this point (cancelled by a concurrent retry's `cancelActiveRunsForMessage`, `chat-loop.service.ts:249-257`, or expired by the deadman), `markStarted` correctly no-ops (0 rows updated) — but the code continues regardless: `run.started`/`model.requested` events are appended to a run whose status is already terminal (violating the \"terminal statuses are immutable\" invariant the repo's own docstrings claim for `run_events`, `runs-repository.ts:188-192`), and `client.streamText(...)` is still invoked, burning cost on a turn that's already been superseded/cancelled/expired.\n- The only safety net for the \"superseded by retry\" sub-case is the same-process `RunAbortRegistry` call at `chat-loop.service.ts:79-81` — there is no DB-level backstop, and (per finding #1) that in-memory registry can itself be stale/racy.\n- Shares root cause with #1: nothing in the pickup→execute path re-verifies \"am I still allowed to run\" immediately before the expensive external call.\n\n---\n\n**4. [HIGH] Inline mode has no deadman/recovery path at all — a process crash mid-turn permanently wedges the chat.**\n\n- `chat-loop.service.ts:86-101`: the `RUN_TIMEOUTS_QUEUE` deadman job is enqueued **only** inside `if (runExecutionMode(this.config) === 'worker')`. In inline mode (current default execution mode per `apps********S.md` / repo `CLAUDE.md`: \"the v0.1 single-model chat loop runs in the apps/api HTTP request path today\"), **no timeout job is ever scheduled**.\n- If the API process crashes/is killed after `persistUserMessageAndRun` commits (run row now non-terminal — `queued` or `running_model`) but before the request thread reaches `onFinish`/`onError`, the run is stranded non-terminal forever: no heartbeat writer, no expiry mechanism exists for it.\n- Because of `runs_chat_inflight_unique` (`db/schema/chats.ts:235-239`, partial unique index on non-terminal statuses), **every subsequent message to that chat 409s forever** (`chat-loop.service.ts:270-275`, `isInflightUniqueViolation`) — `cancelActiveRunsForMessage` only supersedes runs sharing the exact same `messageId`, not any other stuck run in the chat. There's no user-facing \"cancel this run\" path either, since inline mode never returns a `runId` the client can PATCH against (the raw model stream is returned directly, not the bridge).\n- This directly contradicts the schema comment at `db/schema/chats.ts:213`: \"so a chat can never be wedged by a zombie run\" — that guarantee only holds in worker mode. Not covered by any test (only `worker-mode.e2e-spec.ts` tests the deadman).\n\n---\n\n**5. [MEDIUM] Deadman self-rescheduling has no resilience — one failed re-enqueue silently and permanently ends liveness monitoring for that run.**\n\n- `runs-worker.service.ts:114-152` (`checkRunLiveness`): when the verdict is `'alive'`, it re-enqueues itself once (`:147-151`, `this.queue.enqueue(RUN_TIMEOUTS_QUEUE, job, {...})`), **outside** the transaction, with no try/catch.\n- If that specific `enqueue` call throws (transient Postgres blip, pg-boss connection hiccup), the whole `checkRunLiveness` handler throws, so pg-boss retries the **deadman job itself** (`retryLimit: 3`, same `DEFAULT_QUEUE_OPTIONS`) and eventually dead-letters it if the condition persists across all retries.\n- There is no consumer wired to the `.dead` queues in this diff (`RunsWorkerService` only consumes `RUNS_QUEUE`/`RUN_TIMEOUTS_QUEUE`, `:88-99`) — a dead-lettered deadman job is a silent, permanent end to liveness monitoring for that run. If the actual worker later crashes or hangs, nothing will ever expire the run, reproducing the exact wedge described in #4 but triggered by transient infra failure instead of missing inline-mode wiring.\n\n---\n\nNothing else rose to this severity. Compaction (`compaction.service.ts:130-153`) and title generation (`title.service.ts:41-80`) both have real staleness/atomicity guards against concurrent post-turn writers, so I didn't flag them despite finding #1 being able to fire two concurrent `onFinish` calls. The SSE bridge/controller loops (`run-stream-bridge.ts`, `runs.controller.ts`) close/terminate correctly on every path I traced (no leaked `setInterval`/registry entries, no double-close) — I could not construct a standalone reproduction beyond what's already covered by #1/#3, so I didn't list it separately.\n</teammate-message>\n\n<teammate-message teammate_id=\"concurrency-review\" color=\"purple\">\n{\"type\":\"idle_notification\",\"from\":\"concurrency-review\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-02T09:27:40.592Z\",\"idleReason\":\"available\"}\n</teammate-message>\n\n<teammate-message teammate_id=\"concurrency-review\" color=\"purple\" summary=\"Re-send: report already sent, 5 findings\">\nAlready sent the full report (msg_id c3a737ff-8f6d-4207-a1ee-7b8c3c36d6d8) — resending the summary in case it didn't land:\n\nReview complete. 5 findings, 4 HIGH + 1 MEDIUM, all verified against actual code:\n\n1. **[HIGH]** Redelivery double-execution: pg-boss defaults to 900s job expiry (verified in node_modules, never overridden) + retryLimit:3; `markStarted` (runs-repository.ts:94-122) only excludes terminal statuses, not \"must be queued\" — a long-running job redelivered by pg-boss re-enters `executeRun` (run-execution.service.ts:109-117, return value never checked) and fires a second concurrent model call for the same run. Interleaved model.delta events, doubled cost, lost-update race on the assistant message. No test covers redelivery.\n\n2. **[HIGH]** Lost cancellation: TOCTOU in runs-worker.service.ts between the pickup skip-gate (:154-181) and `aborts.register` (:191) — credential resolution (:185) sits in between. A PATCH cancel landing in that window sets `cancel_requested_at` but `aborts.abort()` finds nothing registered yet; `markStarted` never checks `cancelRequestedAt`, so the run completes normally, ignoring the cancel.\n\n3. **[HIGH]** `executeRun` (run-execution.service.ts:109-117) discards `markStarted`'s return value — if the run is already terminal (superseded/expired), it still appends events and makes the paid model call anyway.\n\n4. **[HIGH]** Inline mode never enqueues the deadman job (chat-loop.service.ts:86-101, gated behind `runExecutionMode === 'worker'`). A process crash mid-turn leaves the run non-terminal forever, permanently wedging the chat via `runs_chat_inflight_unique` (schema/chats.ts:235-239) — contradicts that index's own comment \"a chat can never be wedged by a zombie run.\"\n\n5. **[MEDIUM]** Deadman self-reschedule (runs-worker.service.ts:147-151) has no try/catch around its re-enqueue; one transient 